content: Before the 4th anniversary, the life in Class is every active. We will soon start our Spring tournament,
and also, our team of senior members will organise a fast tournament for you as well.
I hope you will all actively participate in them.
Today we will analyse a game from 1999,
Because soon the Theory department will welcome a guest teacher Zhang Jinyu, so today we will look at his game.
Do you all know Zhang Jinyu?
he is the champion in 1st Asia game
he beat simyov as white in d8 opening
As you remember, my game with him in 1999 ended with draw.
From same tournament, we will see his game with Pavel Makarov.
Nowadays, the 5th move is used quite much.
Zhang like this 5 some years ago,but now his doesnt like it=)
And "Zhang" is a surname, Jinyu is given name. Chinese always say surname first.
White player, Pavel Makarov, a strong Russian player.
Before we go on, lets make some opinion check.
What do you think about this variant after 9 moves? Is it better for black or white?
maybe one of those black must be careful, but if defends right, comes out as a winner
It seems this 9th move is quite rare.
In fact, It reminds me of one game on internet many years ago,
where I was beaten by Kawamura.
The game was something like that:
Where is the common 9th move that people use nowadays?
you are correct - people normally use h10 and L10, which in many cases lead to same pattern.
And there it is not so clear to say, who is better, perhaps with careful play white will be better.
Moves 10 and 12 - a tactics of Makarov.
I had never seen such moves before,
what would have been the most natural moves?
I have seen many ideas being played here
If you were black, how would you play the 13th move?
Please all of you suggest a move.
its interesting so many of you show H7 which was Zhang's next move, while in my opinion H7 is not so natural move here
so let me ask frankly, are you simply looking the game record,
seems the attemp to blcok the 2-12 is dangerous
because, the move 13-i10 should be so obvious,
and you should only think of h7, if you are sure i10 is unsuccessful
so, I wonder if you really think by your own mind now
the question here is not to give "perfect" answer,
but I am rather testing you
if I never saw this game before
so, the idea of this lesson is not to hear from you what "he" played.
in fact, perhaps his move was not even good, nor logical.
that way you dont make progress.
I think  maybe zhang have thought about i10
I am sure he thought about i10 at least an hour
it must have been his first thought and checked this thought for long time
and I expected to see i10 from you as well
but for some reason, you all "skipped" 1 hour of thinking result,
so, is it simply copy of record
because if it is, then your answer is not helping me
and I cannot improve your thinking
the point is not about h7 being good or badm
but about what is obvious move here.
therefore, I sometimes reminded you, please NEVER look at game record,
because this way you just replay some others thinking
and you will never know, if YOUR thinking could have been better or worse
killer, are you doing this purposely
h7 is a move that gives an initiative to white
and there will be long positional struggle
while i10 is so obvious - kills all white lines, makes great black base
do you feel "offended" by my speech about the issue of "self thinking"
so you start speaking like "whats wrong with h7"
the point is, you always try to win, before anything else
i10 is the most hopeful win chance,
and I am sure Zhang spent hour to think of it
and then he seeked for other choices, and found h7
and those who now suddenly say h7 as first choice,
it just shows, you are trying to "prove me the Zhang's final conclusion"
but this is not my question!
my question was to see your process of thinking,
I am glad if in the end we can prove h7 is best.
but this is definitely not logical move
so i10 is not a win, but h7 is also doubtful?
and you should have a serious reason, to reject logical i10
i think is good for white
what is the reason to avoid most logical move!
too good is not good, that is )
you mean, Zhang did not want to win too fast,
he maybe chose h7: because he thought i10 is bad, or he wanted to tease his opponent, or he dropped stone there by accident - who knows!
but I wonder why so many of you said H7
I saw the record, but don't know it's zhang's move
coz i have played this 13-h7 for 2 years.
then you should have even more reason to ask yourself,
why deny most logical move that gives black a tempo
just think if 13-i10, black is easy to be surronded by white
while h7 allows white be active
this 13th move was my "todays trap" to all of you
having gotten the feeling that so many of you just follow some game records of masters,
that we are not making any improvement in class,
because you are not telling me your "true thoughts"
therefore, to confirm it, I set this question of 13th move for you today
The renju class is not a movie theatre,
where we only replay some old movie
but where we study our own mind
I know, some of you feel "upset" about my words
but seriously speaking, the class without "honest mind" is useless
even if you saw Zhang's record,
you could simply say "i know zhang played h7, but i10 seems so logical, and i would play there, unless it has some unexpected problem"
it would mean, that despite you are aware of Zhang's move,
you did not stop thinking with your own head
my first thought is g14,but...i found it not good
the class is so silent now..
may i show some moves about my thinking?

may be they didn't see it before. sometimes occure strange things

so, those who said h7, probably solved it
so I am asking them now
what is the problem of i10

blackis activity in up-right side is strong
but seems white can has some materails
so the battle field maybe need to stretch to the other side of the board
maybe black still need to be careful
the detailed development after these moves maybe not so important, just to show the first feeling about this 13, I think black is still strong after 22
but the only hope at the right-up side is not enough
I think maybe white has time to balance now
maybe I didnot seek deep enough here
but my feeling about the situation:
not many people can find such move in a few moments
black needs both support from up and lower side to win the game
yyfcsd has thought deeply about it before
but h7 or some other moves in lower side important too
so, his opinion is based on some long analysis
maybe it is problem of timing
the i10 is logical, but after some analysis,
and we conclude that black will need some other support
Before yy voted for h7, he had deeply thought of i10
so he passed the logical steps
maybe zhang want to search support from lower side and he choose h7
as I said, in the end we might conclude h7 is the greatest move
but the way to that conclusion is long
and if you want to learn how to think in real games,
then you should go through all steps of logic
else you will be in trouble in real tournaments, where no records help you
the variant of yy was great
he showed that move 14 offers strong resistance
but before we put down the i10, lets check some more 15th moves.

meanwhile, let us have check. press button, thanks

Thanks yy for your steps and thoughts
without having a chance to put any stone on board,
because he was playing a live game
which we just did with the help of board and teamwork
So, he seeked for alternative plan,
We do not know if h7 was best or not,
but we can be certain, it was not his first thinking of 13th move.
so, h7 was a result of his hard work.
It is great in many aspects.
but then again, he keeps two potentially great black areas alive - upper and lower area.
And giving up a tempo in such case is not so bad,
especially if you see that white cannot eliminate those black areas by the help of tempo
so there will always be one area left for black.
in Chinese it maybe calls"Deng Zhao"
Makarov took the courage to keep up the tempo,
and trying to fill up the lower are
but perhaps he took too big risk.
he did not try to struggle immediately,
but followed the spirit of h7
which was, to wait until water is clear.
He was trying to make an impression that white will be playing g5 next,
black had to find active solution.
first, with stones 16 and 18 white had completely killed one area of blacks,
and if black still didnt do anything about it, then finally white can kill black's last area too
second reason was a chance - the 18th move offered black a chance, how to eliminate the potential threat of g5, in active manner.
Do you see how L10 eliminates the g5 threat?
I guess Zhang realized, he needs to control i8 point,
so he just took some time to decide,
which of the upper side moves to use,
what other black moves could ensure i8 control?
just to show how many moves can stand against G5 danger
so Zhang finally chose the best of them
which gives best benefit for black side
so, once the tactics of defense was decided (i8 control), then the second task for Zhang was to optimize the black power
Of course, now Makarov had to follow blacks.
if black does not win in this corner,
then the game will go to other areas
and the outcome is hard to be predicted.
But luckily, all ended in that upper corner
nice game.29 connect to upper side through N9, and also it is a vcf threat at the lower side
you can show how black would fail the attack
how can white stop blacks now?
I dont think black cannot win without k6, but k6 makes black win easier, or easy to calculate in tournament
if black want to cut the connection

if white block the lower side

is this black win or not?
the upper side enough to win

he can make sure the upper win
he can slowly think what is happening in upper side
most high level players know how to make such time-buyer moves

and same time, its hard enough, so white must think for some time, how to defend
